To borrow and adapt a principle of @GA4GH, let's collaborate as a community on building a _completely open_ biomedical knowledge base, and compete on the downstream applications. fin/

For example, I love the solution from Phoenix Bioinformatics https://t.co/H1p7g2ERgO, which has a subscription model for the latest data, but releases all data > 1 year old openly. Both supports open data and provides a funding stream for continued development 7/

So I'd ask and encourage everyone who is considering any sort of restriction (be it a fee or any data license) to release part of that data as _completely_ open. Ideally, the CC0 public domain declaration https://t.co/jgXWUqLqPO 6/

Conversely, open and massive knowledge bases (like @wikidata) offer amazing opportunities for the future of AI innovation. I think what ImageNet did for image-based AI, Wikidata could do for knowledge graph based reasoning 5/
Data silos inhibit data mining applications. For more info, see this writeup on the challenges faced by @dhimmel https://t.co/1vYyUkfWw2 and this response to an NIH RFI https://t.co/jqhnwJk4kx 4/

Knowledge is most powerful when it can be integrated and mined together.  Many of the recent advances in AI depend on massive integrated data sets.  And in any situation where some have access and some do not, you've created a data silo. 3/

There was a suggestion this morning that a community knowledge base from @ClinGenResource  could be supported by some sort of fee structure, where people contribute monetarily or in-kind (data, resources). I suggest that this should be done with caution. 2/

Notably, the @parichylab analyzed a triple thyroid receptor mutant, which looks almost identical to wild type! This suggests that thyroid receptors, in the absence of hormone, can act as selective repressors of pigment lineages.
Lauren posted a pre-print (https://t.co/VfuGk5M9lm) a few months back, but the revised story out now has a bunch really cool functional validation experiments.
So in hypothyroid fish, you end up with more immature cells of both types than you should. And the xanthophores don't turn yellow, so you can't pick them up under the microscope.
In melanophores, thyroid hormone allows them to exit the proliferative state and terminally mature. In xanthophores, thyroid hormone is required for them to acquire their yellow pigment.
Surprisingly, Lauren showed that neither model is correct. In fact, thyroid regulates maturation of both pigment cell types.

Backstory: hypothyroid fish don't make yellow pigment cells (xanthophores) and have too many black pigment cells (melanophores). We went in thinking that thyroid hormone either regulates the fraction that choose each pigment fate or amplifies xanthophores over melanophores.

Because it it may be the fastest path to #AGI and it is inherently interesting to understand the conditions in which a simple algorithm can produce general AI (as happened on Earth), I argue that AI-GAs should be considered a new grand challenge of computer science research. 6/6
I also discuss AI-GA-specific safety and ethical considerations. 5/6

Because both are promising, yet the ML community is currently committed to the manual approach, I argue that our community should increase its research investment in the AI-GA approach. To encourage such research, I describe promising work in each of the Three Pillars. 4/6
I argue that either the manual approach or the AI-generating algorithm path could produce general AI first, and both are scientifically worthwhile irrespective of which is the fastest path.  3/6

It is ... unedifying to watch (and participate in when one can as a voter), and of course has real consequences to the 67 million people who live here, not just the 13 or so people currently contesting the Tory leadership.

Will Labour actually have a position which is clear to voters? Or will there be a second referendum potentially as a deal to get the deal through UK parliament. If so - what would be the terms (revoke or deal? Deal or no deal?)
Exploring the druggable space around the Fanconi anemia pathway using machine learning and mechanistic models https://t.co/LirwanS1C7

It seems clear we will be going to (another) bit of brinkmanship in October. Does another Tory leader get eaten by the Europe question? Or does a Tory leader lead the UK into "no deal" and the almost certain serious disruption of UK life  *plus* worse negotiation afterwards?
Finally although the Tory party would like to have a proper majority in Parliament (who wouldn't) they don't have the time or the confidence to call a general election.
(there has a been an all-to-brief attempt for a 4th party in UK politics, with a Macron like pitch. This seemingly has failed)

In the other parties, Labour has continued to be deliberately ambiguous about Brexit, and thus the metropolitan, left-leaning part of the UK has gone back seemingly to the Liberal Democrats who are a long way off power in any form

However, the maths to get a deal through Parliament is hard. The EU might do some window dressing to alter/sweeten the deal, but unlikely to do something substantial (in particular around the Irish border), and this was tried by May multiple times. Does a new leader change this?

This means the candidates are playing up a no-deal Brexit *and* might actually feel that they have to do this (a no-deal Brexit meaning really "screw UK life and negotiate deal with EU from an even worse position"). The madness on the right wing of the Tory party is in full swing

In particular as the Tory party does leadership by winnowing down to 2 candidates, then put to the membership, and the membership is predominately pro-Brexit (older, culturally traditional) means huge benefits for the person who can make it to the last two, pro-Brexit

However, the change is dispiriting. Nigel Farage, the unsuccessful but nevertheless influential leader of ... himself and a general right wing "we want Brexit by any means" is seriously influencing Tory positioning

In some sense you can see this as the UK "not using its time wisely" (as suggest by Donald Tusk). In another way, the issue is the deadlock inside the UK system, so something had to change inside the UK. This is a change.

(The UK Parliamentary system means that the Prime Minister is the person who can form a government - have a majority in UK Parliament, drawn from MPs - so switching Leader of party in government implies switching Prime Minister)

For my international followers, here is my take from Brexit-land UK. First off the inevitable has happened - May has indicated her resignation of the leader of the Tory party and there is an assembled set of Torys lining up to take her place

We make progress all the time, but we rarely overturn a model completely, rather we refine. The earth is flat -> earth is a sphere -> earth is flattened on the top -> shape of the earth is changing all the time... We don't go back and forth between round and flat earth.

This would be "mostly harmless" if it was contained to the introduction sections of papers, but it filters to the wider public and reinforces the idea that scientific results are changing all the time and shouldn't be taken too seriously.
Not that there was anything wrong with these fields of study per se, but the incentives are to exaggerate the challenge to conventional wisdom, not to downplay them.
During the epigenetics bubble, the shtick was to somehow pretend that some observation of methylation and gene expression was a challenge to Darwinism and Lamarck may have been right after all.

The number of papers that were published in the 90s and 2000s that somehow worked in how their results contradicted The Central Dogma of Molecular Biology (even though they didn't) is probably in the low millions.

The conspiracy theory clich√© is that scientists never publish anything against conventional wisdom, but what I see all the time is scientists strawmanning conventional wisdom so they can be against it.

Identities are good, but what about completeness? As suggested by review, I estimated completeness of some assemblies with checkM, comparing completeness scores after each stage of our polishing pipeline (raconx2, medaka, pilonx2). All done automatically by our snakemake pipeline

Alexa and @mason_lab were kind enough to share data ahead of their publication (thanks!), allowing us to perform a robust comparison of our nanopore assemblies. Aligning with minimap2 (-x asm10) makes for some pretty dotplots. HT @ZaminIqbal for the suggestion after our preprint. https://t.co/W7yFAjngEy

Great, so we have contigs, but how can we convince you they aren‚Äôt garbage? Luckily for us, Alexa McIntyre from the @mason_lab had recently published some PacBio isolate sequencing and assemblies for eight of the ten organisms in the Zymo communities https://t.co/gYei4Fhev9.

Unsurprisingly, given the log-distribution of coverage, assembling the log community posed more difficulty. Notably, Listeria the highest abundance organism (~37000√ó coverage) was v.poorly assembled. Very high cov seems to be a problem for the version of wtdbg2 that we used... https://t.co/9sGTM7ys52

Even so, for the even community; genomes near the expected size could be reliably assembled for the 8 bacteria for a variety of parameter conditions. Yeasts proved much harder to assemble but this is expected given their lower coverage. Big contigs from metagenomes can be done! https://t.co/vXUExcgRZI

I made assemblies for log/even from Grid/Prom; varying HPC k-mer size (p), minimum edge weight (e) and read length threshold (L). However, with wtdbg2 under such active development, I gave up trying to find a parameter set that could optimise assembly size & contiguity. https://t.co/B9WnkLoMOL

You‚Äôre probably wondering, did it assemble? I used wtdbg2 (https://t.co/rMrRJcdk2s) to construct metagenomic assemblies of both even & log communities, for GridION and a randomly subsampled 25% PromethION. It was fast, reliable and worked well. But! Parameter choices need care.

We did notice a difference in sequencing speed between the PromethION (mean 419 bp/s and 437 bp/s for even and log) and the GridION (mean speed 352 bp/s and 372 bp/s) which we attributed to different running temperatures on the instrument (39C and 34C respectively).

This permits us to assemble some of the lower abundance organisms from the log-distributed community and detect organisms at extremely low abundance with more confidence. This is crucial for applications where important community members are not present in the highest abundance. https://t.co/gcpaYFdPg1

As @scalene split the sequencing libraries for the two communities between the GridION and PromethION we could directly compare the platforms. My review: it's like having a more powerful microscope. We get 10-fold more data from the PromethION at very similar quality to GridION. https://t.co/bIjHyzQY2d

This is particularly interesting to see in the log community where species are distributed on a log scale, from 89.1% down to 0.000089% relative abundance. We could detect the lowest abundance organism using 4 GridION reads, from just 50 cells of input. Highly sensitive! https://t.co/m8rDV5XJsg

Aligning our @nanopore metagenomic reads to the Illumina-derived isolate references, we observed all 10 microbial species in the community were sequenced in the expected proportion. Cool: long-read metagenomics can be representative of the underlying community.

Additionally, thanks to @ZymoResearch we publish Illumina sequencing runs for each of the 10 isolates, which we assembled individually into draft assemblies. We aligned our long-read nanopore metagenomics reads to the drafts to estimate taxon abundance without a database. https://t.co/0n7Wo05Ycm

We release 14 & 16 Gbp of sequence from the GridION; with 150 & 153 Gbp from the beastly PromethION, for the even and log distributed standards respectively. Read N50 ranged 5.3 - 5.4 Kbp over the four runs. 4.2 TB of signal is available to anyone who wants to take a cluster down https://t.co/YMJU2vf0Da

As we begin to make big decisions with genomic data, it is vital that experiments are conducted correctly and that sequencing and bioinformatics pipelines can be validated. Yet, there is a lack of available testing data, particularly for metagenomics and especially long-reads.

Mock communities like these are really useful for both the lab and bioinformatics as positive controls. As the samples are validated to contain a known distribution of the taxa, they could be used to check that DNA extractions, or say, taxonomic classifiers have worked properly.

The goal of this work was to make available a really deep, long-read dataset for some community standards. We used two synthetic ‚Äúmock‚Äù microbial communities manufactured by @ZymoResearch, containing a mix of gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria, and two yeasts. https://t.co/1dTH9oXDjC

But there is also what I think of as the internal environment of an organism, which is the particular sets of physical and historical elements that also shape how a species can evolve. An example would be the genetic code. 2/

Yes this is a profound claim, and one with a lot of implications for biology and how to study biology. When we talk about evolution we discuss environment selecting and constraining. Remarkable vision as well from @wellcometrust and @The_MRC in setting up @uk_biobank and great leadership from Rory Collins and his team.

The world owes a debt to these 500,000 middle aged (or older), middle class Brits who are the best modelled/understood humans in the world, underpinning both basic and applied clinical research in so many fields

The other star was @uk_biobank which I said was the key resource used by around 25% of the presentations, including @HannahCurrant1's eye OCT. UK BioBank will have full exomes soon, full genomes likely, 100,000 MRIs. It is ... awesome.
But it was far more than PRS. The clonal expansions in blood was very interesting (another thing with pretty clear path to clinical research and potential implementation)
It means I think we can be confident we can make "robust" PRSs for many traits including many diseases. The next question is how to use them - both in research and potentially in clinical practice.

It terms of "all in" modelling for PRS I think it's going to be really hard to beat the @Genomicsplc crew (@genemodeller et al) - not just for the theory (eg clever power borrowing across GWAS) but also for the engineering / pipelining.

This thorough exploration and good flip flopping between theory and data, careful intra and inter study design means this is going to be on solid ground (and perhaps more importantly, we will understand where the weak ground is)

Because PRS is a hot topic at the moment I found today's session really interesting. Taking a step back, the statistical genetics community are getting really stuck into the details of PRS - what works or not, where are PRSs fragile or robust

I didn't get a bonus out of this incident, or even anything I could put on my resume. (Heck. I could have made up this entire story, for all you really know.)It was simply worth it just to prevent the future stress I would have experienced on the job.
After I disabled the logic bombs, I spoke to my supervisor about what had happened.Their expression was memorable when they realized how much wasted money I had just saved the lab.
They didn't know my skill-set.

The sequential logic bombs had been designed to force us to have to fly in the super-expensive tech from the vendor, who would have been reasonable in assuming medical testing staff wouldn't be able to troubleshoot their hardware effectively to disable them.
Then I looked at all the other stations in the machine (something like 10 more). The network credentials for each had been set to expire on different dates, spread out over most of a year.
Once I figured out the issue, I re-established the station's credentials and set them to never expire.

As I couldn't do much else, I spent some time investigating the problem. It turned out that workstation's password to access the main computer on the network had expired.As the workstations were headless, it wasn't immediately clear this had happened. The machine just stopped.

One day one of the workstations lost connectivity to the rest of the system. This was bad. No work could be done in the lab. We were going to have to fly in a tech again.It was late on a Friday, so we had a couple days before we could even make the request for the tech.

We had to fly in a designer/tech from the vendor to resolve these issues, at some rate comparable to my yearly income... for a couple days. They claimed to not understand why we were having these issues, but gladly sent their tech to assist us.

The robots needed service more often than expected and when one had an error, the entire system ground to a halt. The system was supposed to be fault tolerant, pausing when an error happened. Instead, every sample that was being processed in the machine was lost & needed redone.

They were all networked together and then managed by a single computer at the head of the overall system. There was no network connection to the outside world. It was pretty secure in that way.The machine mostly worked the way it was supposed to.

The system consisted of a series of workstations, with robotic arms and tables that would handle/process specimens and then move them along to the next station when they were done.The stations were running a windows operating system.

Let me tell you about a logic bomb that a vendor installed in hardware a lab I used to work in relied on.The lab did medical sample testing. They had just purchased and installed a robotic automation system that would run all the testing steps, faster/better than prior systems.

Applying ANEVA-DOT to muscle disease patients (from @beryl_bbc , @dgmacarthur et al.) showed really good specificity and sensitivity in previously diagnosed patients, and indicated new diagnoses that has been missed in previous WES, WGS and RNA-seq analyses.

Our ANEVA Dosage Outlier Test then uses allelic expression data from any individual and the population reference variation to find the genes where the individual seems to carry a variant with an unusually strong effect on gene expression.

Genes with low amount of genetic regulatory variation are enriched for coding constraint and rare disease genes - building a link between intolerance for dosage variation regardless of variation type.

We developed a new method, Analysis of Expression VAriation (ANEVA) to model allelic expression data to quantify population genetic regulatory variation for each gene. This was applied in multi-tissue #GTEx data...

Our aim is to stimulate an open discussion about the potential benefits and limitations  of AI-guided treatment assignments in precision oncology programs. So we can minimize collective treatment regret.  /END

Additionally, the number of targeted therapeutics tested in clinical trials has grown rapidly, prompting the introduction of modern master trial designs, such as baskets, umbrellas and platforms, thereby improving the throughput of efficacy testing.

The contextual bandits (or full RL) model could also be applied directly to clinical data. For example, @atulbutte has repeatedly shown that @UCSF T2DM patients suffer from the same problem of monotherapy selection, including data with updated patient states after each action. https://t.co/vlcJtUAtvN

Our future work: 1) Run this model in a validation cohort, 2) Expand the number of tested treatments; cisplatin is a limited reference, and 3) see if the model can identify unknown mutational signatures when blinded to therapeutic guidelines and associated SNPs.

Results: We compared model performance against other benchmarks & current therapeutic protocols. Protocols perform better than random treatment assignment. However, our in-silico models outperformed current protocols and availability of genomic information increased performance. https://t.co/Iak6byAX3D

We used Bayesian neural networks to subsequently chose the best treatment for a randomly selected cell line by observing the genomic data. Based on the treatment decision, the agent was rewarded with the in-vitro drug response the cancer cell line showed to the agent.
We used UMAP to reduce ~18,000 genomic features into 20 and found that cell lines clustered by tissue type. https://t.co/GYXlrFfhVq
In parallel, we manually curated the therapeutic protocols for each compound that reflect current clinical evidence based on the @MDAndersonNews knowledge base.

We curated and processed a dataset of 1000 cancer cell lines and their response to 7 therapeutics from @Francesco_i0ri0 work at the @Garnettlab. For each cell line, we have SNV, CNV, and gene expression data.

We formalized selection of targeted therapy as a contextual bandit problem, via @jasper @GoogleAI's Deep Bayesian Bandits Showdown. We hypothesize that unfiltered genomic information may be more predictive of response than current therapeutic protocols. https://t.co/ZG511NZsug

So, what if we could teach a neural network to use both current clinical evidence and raw genomic data to guide clinical decision making? Could it-over time-learn to perform better than current clinical standards and allow us to treat more patients with the most effective drugs?

Two main clinical problems:1. High selectiveness - only 4.9% of cancer patients benefit from genome-targeted therapy. https://t.co/pdRwWMcuKy?2. High compassionate use - doesn't contribute to the new clinical evidence, limiting new indications for effective drugs.

Our supporters include @cardiomyopathy, the UK specialist national charity for people affected by cardiomyopathy.  They believe this will benefit patients, and are helping us deliver this.

Unfortunately, sometimes it can be difficult for people to be involved in research because clinicians  or researchers are unwilling to share data.  @thehearthive is open, collaborative, and puts patients in the driving seat  #openaccess #openscience

Key features for accessibility include online self-directed research consent, collection of health data direct from participants as well as digital records, and postal kits to collect saliva for DNA analysis. Participants control their own data, and decide who can analyse it.
We also often want to follow people over time which is costly for all.

Researchers also struggle to reach patients. We may want to reach 1000s of people for contemporary genetic studies, or a v specific group to trial a treatment for a particular rare condition.  Either way, old-fashioned recruitment in waiting rooms is not scalable & sustainable

It starts with patients telling us they want to be involved in research. Benefits include empowerment, taking an active step to deal with disease, and sometimes improved health from new experimental therapies. But people find it difficult to get involved.https://t.co/zh1yhdTvLN

I simulated a population with 500K individuals which split 10K generations ago into two populations of 250K with no gene flow between them. Median Phi_st for this set of simulations was 0.023 - right in line with what we observed in our dataset. Lots of zeros too.

These species fall into that area of population genetic parameter space with high effective size and high gene flow that I have taken to calling the "Waples Zone" F_st and its analogs are expected to be very close to zero in the Waples Zone. All noise, little signal.
